The '''1889<U+2013>90 Currie Cup''' was the inaugural edition of the [[Sunfoil Series|Currie Cup]], the premier [[first-class cricket]] tournament in South Africa. The 1889<U+2013>90 competition involved just two teams, [[Gauteng cricket team|Transvaal]] and [[Griqualand West cricket team|Kimberley]]. The two sides played a single, three-day match, which was won by Transvaal by six wickets.

Both sides made low scores in their first innings; Kimberley, who had opted to bat first, were dismissed for 98 runs, and in their reply Transvaal reached 117, a lead of just 19 runs. In the second innings, they both fared better; a century from [[Bernard Tancred]] helped Kimberley to a total of 235, but Transvaal reached their total in 38 five-ball [[Over (cricket)|overs]], helped by a century from [[Monty Bowden]].

==Background==
[[File:Donald Currie Vanity Fair 21 June 1884.jpg|thumbnail|upright|Sir [[Donald Currie]] donated the Currie Cup, to be awarded to the best first-class side in South Africa.]]
[[First-class cricket]] was first played in South Africa in the previous 1888<U+2013>89 season, when Robert Warton managed a side which toured the country, playing against representative teams from each of the provinces, and two matches against [[South Africa national cricket team|South Africa]], which were later adjudged to have [[Test cricket]] status.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/south-africa-domestic-2011/content/current/story/259976.html |title=South Africa domestic cricket: A brief history ... |publisher=[[ESPNcricinfo]] |accessdate=19 January 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricketarchive.com/Archive/Events/8/RG_Wartons_XI_in_South_Africa_1888-89.html |title=RG Warton's XI in South Africa 1888/89 |publisher=[[CricketArchive]] |accessdate=19 January 2013}}</ref> During that tour, [[Donald Currie]] donated the [[Sunfoil Series|Currie Cup]] to be awarded to the team which performed best against the touring side; which was judged to be [[Griqualand West cricket team|Kimberley]].<ref>{{cite book|url=http://books.google.co.uk/books?id=mYBtMajLAaAC&pg=PA117&lpg=PA117 |title=Sports around the World |editor-last=Nauright |editor-first=John |year=2012 |isbn=978-1-59884-300-2 |publisher=ABC-CLIO, LLC |location=Santa Barbara, California |accessdate=19 January 2013}}</ref> In other first-class matches during the 1889<U+2013>90 season, Kimberley faced [[Natal cricket team|Natal]] twice, winning both matches.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/3/3519.html |title=Kimberley v Natal: Other First-Class matches in South Africa 1889/90 |publisher=CricketArchive |accessdate=19 January 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/3/3521.html |title=Kimberley v Natal: Other First-Class matches in South Africa 1889/90 |publisher=CricketArchive |accessdate=19 January 2013}}</ref> Transvaal did not play any first-class cricket prior to their Currie Cup contest with Kimberley.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cricketarchive.com/Archive/Teams/0/364/First-Class_Matches.html |title=First-Class Matches played by Transvaal |publisher=CricketArchive |accessdate=19 January 2013}}</ref>

Transvaal challenged Kimberley for the Currie Cup in 1890, the first such challenge for the trophy. A number of the team selections were controversial: the selection committee for Transvaal chose [[Aubrey Smith]] and [[Monty Bowden]], both of whom had remained in South Africa after touring as part of the [[England cricket team]] the previous year, and [[Charlie Finlason]], who played the majority of his cricket for the opposition Kimberley team. Finlason, a newspaper journalist, had fallen out with Smith after writing a number of articles criticising him and the English side. When Finlason was selected for Transvaal, Smith<U+2014>who was captaining the side<U+2014>made him bat at number eleven.<ref name="empire">{{cite book |url= |title=Empire & Cricket: The South African Experience |last1=Murray |first1=Bruce K |last2=Vahed |first2=Goolam H |publisher=Unisa Press |year=2009 |pages=34<U+2013>57}}</ref>

==Match==

===Summary===
The match began on Saturday 5 April 1890 at the [[Eclectics Cricket Club Ground]] in [[Kimberley, Northern Cape|Kimberley]]. The [[Toss (cricket)|toss]] was won by the Kimberley [[Captain (cricket)|captain]], [[Walter Woodthorpe]], who opted to bat first. [[Bernard Tancred]] and [[Robert Snedden]] opened the batting, and scored 25 [[Run (cricket)|runs]] together before the first [[wicket]] fell. The Transvaal bowlers took three more wickets for the addition of just 27 runs, leaving Kimberley on 52 for 4. The batsmen then shared a [[Partnership (cricket)|partnership]] of 40 runs, but upon the loss of the next wicket, Kimberley suffered a collapse, and were eventually bowled out for 98 runs. Tancred top-scored for the side, accruing 42 runs, but only two other batsmen reached double figures; Snedden and [[John Coghlan (cricketer)|John Coghlan]], both of whom scored 13. Transvaal only used three bowlers during the innings; [[Aubrey Smith]] and [[Bentley Wimble]] each took four wickets, while [[Charles Vintcent]] took the remaining two.<ref name="camatch">{{cite web|url=http://www.cricketarchive.com/Archive/Scorecards/3/3534.html |title=Kimberley v Transvaal: Currie Cup 1889/90 |publisher=CricketArchive |accessdate=19 January 2013}}</ref>

Transvaal began their reply strongly; their openers, [[Monty Bowden]] and [[John Hickson (cricketer)|John Hickson]] put on 69 runs for the first wicket, the majority being scored by Bowden. Once they lost their first wicket, the team continued to lose wickets at regular intervals; the second-highest partnership of the innings was the 17 runs made for the tenth, or last, wicket. [[George Glover (cricketer)|George Glover]] was the best of the bowlers, collecting six wickets. Glover and [[Albert Rose-Innes]] bowled the majority of the [[Over (cricket)|overs]], and took nine of the wickets between them. Bowden's score of 63 was substantially the best by any batsman in the innings, only [[John Piton]], [[Spranger Harrison]] and Hickson scored more than 10 runs, and none managed as many as 20.<ref name="camatch"/>

The third innings of the match gave Kimberley a second attempt at batting on the first day; they lost wickets regularly through the afternoon, but opener Tancred remained at the crease throughout, finishing the day unbeaten on 55, with the team on 100 for six. The match resumed on Monday 7 April 1890, with no play scheduled for the Sunday. After the early loss of Rose-Innes for 20 runs, [[Charles Rutherfoord]] joined Tancred. The pair scored 97 runs together, taking the score up to 226. Three quick wickets then ended the Kimberley innings; they scored 235 runs from 83 overs, in which Tancred scored a century, hitting 106 runs before being [[leg before wicket]] to Bowden. Vintcent took the most wickets for Transvaal, claiming four for 70. Smith claimed two wickets, and Bowden, who was designed on the scorecard as the team's [[wicket-keeper]] also claimed two wickets from the three overs that he bowled.<ref name="camatch"/>

Transvaal batted rapidly in their second innings, reaching the required total to win the match inside the second day of the match, which had been scheduled for three days in total. Opening batsman Bowden batted throughout the whole innings, remaining not out on 126 when his side won the match. He was joined at the end by Vintcent, who scored 60 runs in a partnership of 126 runs between the two players. Kimberley tried six different bowlers in an effort to bowl Transvaal out, but only Rose-Innes and [[Irvine Grimmer]] took wickets, claiming two apiece.<ref name="camatch"/>

